# Delegation Pattern

How the lead/orchestrator hands work to another agent and waits for the result.

## `mc delegate` — the only correct way to wait on a subtask

```bash
mc delegate "Research: <concrete question(s)>" \
  --to Researcher \
  --description "<exactly what's needed + all sub-questions + guardrails + DoD>" \
  --priority high
```

This atomically creates: a subtask with `parent_task_id`/`assigned_agent_id`/
`callback_agent_id`, blocks the parent task with `blocked_by_task_id`, and posts
a "Delegated to ..." progress comment. No operator approval — pure orchestration.
The watchdog reactivates the parent to `in_progress` once the subtask is `done`.

**All research tasks go to Researcher** — it parallelizes internally via
subagents. Never split one research question across multiple agents.

**Fire-and-forget** (rare — no callback wait):
```bash
mc delegate "..." --to <agent> --description "..." --no-callback
```

**FORBIDDEN:** creating a task manually and then setting `mc blocked` as
separate calls — that produces false-positive operator approvals and skips
the callback link. Always `mc delegate`.

## Telegram boundary in the subtask brief

`mc telegram` does NOT belong in the worker's acceptance criteria — the
dispatcher sends the final report. The backend enforces this with 422
"Subtask cannot send Telegram". In the `--description`, write explicitly:
> "No `mc telegram` — I ({{ operator_name }}'s orchestrator) consolidate after
> your `mc finish` and send the final report with file attachment."

Exception: `autonomous_telegram=true` in the brief for long-running watch tasks.

## No busy-waiting

While the parent is `blocked` on a callback, do not poll or "check again in a
minute" — end your turn. The dispatch cascade re-activates you automatically
once the upstream is done.

## Delegation vs. Briefing vs. Note

| Scenario | Call | Effect |
|---|---|---|
| New sub-task for a worker | `mc delegate "..." --to <agent> --description "..."` | New sub-task, dispatch, parent → blocked with callback |
| Briefing/wake on an already-assigned task | `mc comment handoff "<text>"` | `handoff` is a deliverable comment_type → worker wakes on next poll |
| Routine note / audit entry | `mc comment message "<text>"` (default) | Audit log only, not delivered to another agent |

**Forbidden:** `mc comment message "..."` targeted at another agent's task — the
worker never sees it. Use `mc comment handoff` (existing task) or `mc delegate`
(new task) instead.

## Consensus (multi-agent validation)

```bash
curl -s -X POST "$MC_API_URL/api/v1/agent/consensus" \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $MC_AGENT_TOKEN" -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"question": "...", "agent_ids": ["<uuid-1>", "<uuid-2>"]}'
```

Creates N subtasks (one per agent), dispatches in parallel, the watchdog
detects completion. Use instead of manual subtask creation when the same
input is needed from multiple agents.
